"Oh, Warry's well enough," the bishop answered. "But Warry's an uncertain
                        quantity. He's a fine, clean fellow, with all kinds of possibilities;
                        butthey're possibilities!"

Wheaton had never seen her so grave. He was sincerely sorry for her trouble,
                        and he tried, to say so. There was something appealing in her unusual calm;
                        the low tones of her voice were not wasted on him.

"'Though I be mad, I shall not wake;
I shall not fall to common sight;
Only the god himself may take
This music out of my blood, this glory out of my breath,
This lift, this rapture, this singing might,
And love that outlasts death.'"

If it had been true; ifif we had been engaged, it would not be so wretched;
                        but thisoh, it hurts me!" She lay back in her chair. Her eyes were
                        over-bright; her words ended in a wail.

